WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:11.280
Before any of the fancy tables make sense, you only need
two numbers. Just two. Get these, and the entire dashboard
opens up.

2
00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:31.632
Every trade does the same thing. You get in, price wiggles
around, and eventually the trade is over. While it's open,
it travels some distance against you, and some distance in
your favor. Those two distances are the only things this
dashboard truly cares about. Here's the raw trade log,
every trade you've recorded, with both numbers logged on
each one.

3
00:00:32.232 --> 00:00:47.424
The first number is MAE, maximum adverse excursion. The
worst the trade went against you before it resolved. Think
of it as the heat you had to sit through to stay in the
trade. That is your risk. Summed across all your trades,
it lives right here, in Risk and MAE.

4
00:00:48.024 --> 00:01:01.992
The second number is MFE, maximum favorable excursion. The
best the trade ran in your favor before it ended. That's
the profit that was on the table, whether you grabbed it
or not. Across your trades, it's summarized here, in
Profit and MFE.

5
00:01:02.592 --> 00:01:18.552
Both are stored as a percent of price, never as dollars.
Here's why that matters so much. A tenth of a percent
means the same thing on a twenty thousand dollar Nasdaq
contract and a two thousand dollar Russell contract.
Percent makes every trade, on every instrument, finally
comparable.

6
00:01:19.152 --> 00:01:44.064
A trader named John Sweeney built an entire method on
this. He realized that whether one single trade won or
lost is almost noise. But how far your trades typically
run against you, and how far they run for you, across a
hundred trades, that's signal. That's a measurable edge.
Your stop comes from the MAE side. Your target comes from
the MFE side. And everything else on this dashboard is
just these two numbers, sliced a hundred different ways.

7
00:01:44.664 --> 00:01:51.552
Two numbers per trade. How far against you, and how far
for you. Log them honestly, and the rest of the machine
does the work.
